a:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 mb-6 not-prose","children":["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2.5 border-l-4 border-yellow-400/50 pl-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Pentagon bets $1B on non-Chinese drones from Ukraine"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Shrike 10 Fiber’s hardware limits remain untested at scale"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"DJI’s supply chain dominance isn’t just about components"}]]}]]}]}]
b:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["The US Army’s ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.defense.gov/News/Releases/Release/Article/3733423/","children":"Drone Dominance program"}]," just placed a billion-dollar bet on an unlikely candidate: a ‘mysterious’ Ukrainian startup whose ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.techradar.com/news/ukrainian-drones-shrike-10-fiber-and-f10-impress-pentagon-earning-contracts-in-a-billion-dollar-drone-dominance-program-focused-on-non-chinese-components","children":"Shrike 10 Fiber and F10 drones"}]," impressed the Pentagon for one reason above all others. They contain ",["$","em",null,{"children":"zero"}]," Chinese-sourced components—a rarity in a market where ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.droneii.com/drone-market-report-2023","children":"DJI controls ~70% of the US commercial drone sector"}]," and even military-grade systems often rely on Chinese semiconductors or batteries.\nThis isn’t just geopolitical posturing. The ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.congress.gov/bill/117th-congress/house-bill/7776/text","children":"2023 NDAA"}]," already banned federal agencies from buying DJI drones over espionage concerns, leaving a gap for alternatives that can actually ",["$","em",null,{"children":"fly"}],"—not just pass a parts inspection. Ukrainian Defense Drones Tech Corporation’s win suggests their hardware meets basic performance thresholds, but the real question is whether ‘non-Chinese’ translates to ‘non-problematic’ in the field.\nEarly specs for the Shrike 10 Fiber—",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.armyupress.army.mil/Journals/Military-Review/English-Edition-Archives/July-August-2023/Ukraines-Drone-War/","children":"a 10kg fixed-wing drone"}]," with a 100km range—sound competitive on paper. Yet ‘competitive’ in a controlled Pentagon demo isn’t the same as ‘reliable’ in a dusty Afghan outpost or a Florida hurricane response. The F10’s payload capacity and battery life under real-world thermal stress remain unproven at scale, and the ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.gao.gov/products/gao-22-105166","children":"history of rapid drone failures"}]," in US military programs suggests hardware maturity is a bigger hurdle than component sourcing."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/ukraines-drones-can-they-outfly-dji-without-chinas/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Od labsa do prakse: Ukrajinski dronovi moraju dokazati više od ‘bez-kineske’ etikete","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"Od labsa do prakse: Ukrajinski dronovi moraju dokazati više od ‘bez-kineske’ etikete"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["The bigger friction point isn’t the drones themselves—it’s the ecosystem. DJI’s dominance isn’t just about cheap chips; it’s about a decade of refined autopilot algorithms, global repair networks, and ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.faa.gov/uas","children":"regulatory certifications"}]," that let operators fly without jumping through hoops. Ukrainian drones may avoid Chinese silicon, but can they avoid the ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.defensedaily.com/defense-industry-ukraine-war-exposes-gaps-in-u-s-defense-industrial-base/ukraine-war/","children":"supply chain chaos"}]," that’s plagued other non-Chinese defense tech? Early contracts are a start, but mass deployment requires parts availability, pilot training pipelines, and—critically—a track record of ","$L13"," falling out of the sky when GPS jamming starts.\nThere’s also the matter of what ‘non-Chinese’ actually buys you. The Pentagon’s ban targets ","$L14",", yet ","$L15"," stem from software, not hardware. If Ukrainian drones run on open-source flight stacks (as many military UAS do), their cyber risks might mirror DJI’s—just with a different flag on the box. And while the Shrike’s fiber-composite airframe is a legitimate innovation, ","$L16"," is its own nightmare of quality control and cost overruns.\nThe most plausible near-term use case isn’t replacing DJI’s ","$L17"," in police departments, but filling niche gaps where Chinese components are a dealbreaker: special forces ops, critical infrastructure inspections, or ","$L18"," where supply chain assurance matters more than absolute performance. Even there, the real test isn’t the first contract—it’s the 100th drone still flying after a year in the desert."]}]]}]
